The overall goal of the implementing mechanism is to support the GoB in the national HIV response by training and mentoring health care providers to enable them to deliver high quality clinical services. This is consistent with goal 4 of the Partnership Framework. Activities include treatment, care and support, TB/HIV, health informatics and laboratory services. The activities are meant to be nationwide in scope and focus mainly on enhancing the skills of health care workers providing services to persons infected with HIV and/or TB. The cooperative agreement will integrate training efforts that previously were covered under four cooperative agreements all of which end in CY 2014 (Botswana Harvard Partnership x2, Baylor and University of Pennsylvania). Integrating these activities in one cooperative agreement should result in cost savings by more efficient use of existing resources. Part of the implementing partner’s responsibility is to build capacity within the MOH so that training efforts can be managed in future without external support. Each component of the cooperative agreement has a monitoring and evaluation plan. Many of these rely on PIMS, the Patient Information Management System, which was developed with PEPFAR/B support and is currently in use nationwide. Funding for health informatics activities in this cooperative agreement is for onsite support and mentoring of GoB staff on PIMS. As a new FOA there is no pipeline. Expenditure analysis was first done in Botswana late in CY 2013. Data are not expected to be available till after submission of this COP.

Food Security Innovation Lab: Collaborative Research on Assets and Market Access (BASIS/AMA), will conduct an impact evaluation of the Girls Education activity. The Girls Education overall objective is to enhance the capacity of families and communities to support, protect and care for OVC, and services will be prioritized and focused on addressing the most critical needs of OVC as well as the members of their family. The proposed program will likely contain a range of interventions or combinations of interventions including childcare support (to remove some of the burden of caring for younger siblings from older girls), school assistance support designed to support secondary school attendance for older girls, nutrition education/counseling for caregivers intended to improve nutrition especially in younger children, and, finally,economic strengthening intervention aimed at improving the economic well-being of the overall family.  As currently envisioned, the economic strengthening component will involve the promotion of village-level savings groups. The Goal of this Impact Evaluation is: To build evidence of interventions that improve the wellbeing of vulnerable children, to inform future programming. Purchased/leased vehicles are not planned under this mechanism.  The evaluation will also employ a gender lens where applicable.
